#Text=Cromwell Lee
#Text=Cromwell Lee ( died 1601 ) was the son of Sir Anthony , and a younger brother of Elizabeth I 's champion , Sir Henry Lee .
#Text=He was the compiler of an Italian-English dictionary .
#Text=Family
#Text=Cromwell Lee was the youngest son of Sir Anthony Lee and Margaret Wyatt , sister of the poet Sir Thomas Wyatt .
#Text=He had three brothers and five sisters . [ 1 ] [ 2 ] [ 3 ] [ 4 ]
#Text=He also had two illegitimate half-brothers who were born before his father 's second marriage to their mother , Anne Hassall . [ 5 ]
#Text=For details concerning his siblings , see the article on his father , Sir Anthony Lee .
#Text=Career
#Text=Cromwell Lee 's mother , Margaret Wyatt , by Hans Holbein
#Text=Cromwell Lee 's eldest brother , Sir Henry Lee , by Anthonis Mor
#Text=His father is thought to have been in the service of Thomas Cromwell by 1532 , and had an active career at court and in local government in Buckinghamshire .
#Text=His eldest brother , Sir Henry Lee , was a prominent courtier and Elizabeth I 's champion .
#Text=In about 1572 Cromwell Lee matriculated at St John 's College , Oxford , but left without taking a degree . [ 6 ]
#Text=He travelled in Italy for some years . [ 6 ] [ 7 ]
#Text=He appears to have been close to his eldest brother , Sir Henry Lee , and to his illegitimate half-brother , Sir Richard Lee .

#Text=Through his first marriage to Mary Blundell , Sir Richard Lee held leases of two manors in Hook Norton which became the subject of subsequent litigation with John Croker , Mary Blundell 's son by her first marriage .
#Text=Pleadings from 1587 reveal that Sir Richard Lee had sublet these leases to his half-brother , Cromwell , who resided on the Hook Norton property with his family .

#Text=The controversy over the leases is briefly mentioned in Leicester 's Commonwealth ( 1584 ) , where the author refers to the Earl of Leicester 's oppressive ' dealing with Master Richard Lee for his manor of Hook Norton ( if I fail not in the name ) ' . [ 8 ]
#Text=In addition to the leases at Hook Norton , Cromwell Lee had property at Cutteslowe in Oxfordshire , and served as a Justice of the Peace , ' of no very good repute ' for that county .
#Text=However he resided principally in Oxford itself , where in 1590 he was granted licence by the Vice-Chancellor of the University to eat meat in Lent .
#Text=According to Chambers , ' more than one Oxford epigram describes his morals in the grossest terms ' . [ 9 ]

#Text=On 23 September 1590 Sir Henry Lee was commissioned to investigate the murder of one Nicholas Crane , and his brother Cromwell was joined with him in the investigation , together with William Spencer of Yarnton , and Walter Culpepper of Kent . [ 10 ]

#Text=In 1599 Sir Henry Lee purchased the tenancy in chief of the manor of Spelsbury , held of the crown , in Cromwell Lee 's name , taking a bond from Cromwell which allowed Sir Henry enjoyment of the manor during Cromwell 's lifetime and the reversionary interest at Cromwell 's death . [ 11 ]
#Text=In 1600
#Text=Sir Henry Lee transferred to Cromwell his interest in the advowson of Charlbury . [ 12 ]
#Text=Sir Henry was convalescing at Woodstock when he heard news of the Earl of Essex 's rebellion in February 1601 .
#Text=According to Chambers , ' his first impulse was to repair to London with his brother Cromwell , but a relapse held him ' .
#Text=Whether Cromwell Lee went to London on his own at the time is not known . [ 13 ]
#Text=Cromwell Lee compiled part of an Italian – English dictionary , completing it up to the word tralignato . [ 7 ]
#Text=He gave the work to the library of St John 's College , Oxford , [ 6 ] ' where a fair copy of it , transcribed by Thomas Potticary , M.A. of that College , yet remains ' .
#Text=Although unfinished , it is said to have been ' as big as a church bible ' . [ 14 ]
#Text=He died in December 1601 , [ 6 ] while resident in the parish of St Cross Holywell , Oxford . [ 7 ] [ 9 ]
#Text=His eldest brother , Sir Henry , was his heir at law , and in his own will dated 6 October 1609 directed that tombs be set up for his brother , Cromwell , and other family members .
#Text=It seems , however , that this was never done . [ 15 ]
#Text=An epitaph , attributed to ' a humorous student ' of Oxford , stated that at his death Cromwell Lee ' gave nothing to the poor/But half to his bastards and half to his whore ' . [ 14 ]
#Text=His portrait , attributed to Marcus Gheeraerts the Younger , was included in an exhibition at Oxford in 1904 ; however , its present whereabouts are unknown . [ 16 ] [ 17 ] [ 18 ]
#Text=Marriage
#Text=In 1575 he married Mary Harcourt , widow of Richard Taverner ( d.1575 ) of Woodeaton , Clerk of the Signet to Edward VI .

#Text=She was one of the eight daughters of Sir John Harcourt ( d. 19 February 1566 ) of Stanton Harcourt by Margaret Barentyne , [ 19 ] [ 20 ] and by her first marriage to Richard Taverner was the great-grandmother of Anthony Wood . [ 21 ]
#Text=There appear to have been no children of the marriage . [ 9 ]

#Text=The family of Lees of Barna , Tipperary , claimed descent from Cromwell Lee , and according to Chambers this may have been through an illegitimate son , Robert Lee of New Woodstock , son of Cromwell 's servant , Joan Hopkins alias Hatton .

#Text=In his will he left Joan some kine and household goods at Cutteslowe , to her daughter Alice a marriage portion of £10 , and to Robert his household furniture and his leases from Merton College .
#Text=He made Joan and Robert his residuary legatees .
#Text=She later married one Thomas Aylwin or Ayleward of Eversley , a witness to the will . [ 9 ]
#Text=He is also reputed to have been the father of one John Lee ( d.1609 ) who was a Fellow of St John 's College , Oxford , and graduated MA in 1591 .
#Text=John Lee 's mother was named Anne , and he had a brother , Francis Lee , as well as a sister married to a husband surnamed Tote .

#Text=As Chambers notes , there was a family connection , as John Lee held the livings of Fleet Marston and Wootton , but he could not have been a legitimate son ' or Sir Henry Lee would not have been Cromwell 's heir at law ' . [ 22 ]
